'''Buntingford Almshouses''' is a grade II* [[listed building]] on the High street of the Hertfordshire town of [[Buntingford]]. The building was erected in 1684 by the mathematician and astronomer Bishop [[Seth Ward (bishop)|Seth Ward]]<ref name=ehlisting>{{NHLE|num=1101350 |desc=|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> who was born in the town. The architect was probably the celebrated scientist and architect, [[Robert Hooke]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Batten|first1=M. I.|title=THE ARCHITECTURE OF DR. ROBERT HOOKE, F.R.S.|journal=The Volume of the Walpole Society|date=1936–1937|volume=25|page=110}}</ref>
The building, located next to St Peter's church, is built of brick around three sides of a courtyard. The heritage listing describes the building as ''"A classical almshouses of 1684 of outstanding interest."''<ref name=ehlisting />
Having previously been used as the town hospital, the building is now run by a charity to provide accommodation for elderly people in the town.<ref>{{EW charity|240885}}</ref>
